{:proof/problem-id "apm-a93J06", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (unit disk, analytic function, derivative bound, desired inequality) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target only concludes the estimate after all hypotheses) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (it’s a precise Schwarz-type inequality worth proving on its own) · notes: The radial integral combined with the derivative bound gives the sharp \\(|z|^2/2\\) estimate, so formalizing exactly that inequality is the right target.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Derive the estimate |f(z)| ≤ |z|^2/2 from the hypotheses f(0)=f'(0)=0 and |f'(z)|≤1 on the unit disk.\"\n :terms [{:name \"radial integral formula\"\n          :meaning \"For analytic f with f(0)=0, f(z)=∫_0^1 z f'(tz) dt.\"\n          :needed-because \"Provides an exact expression whose integrand involves f'.\"}\n         {:name \"derivative bound\"\n          :meaning \"|f'(tz)| ≤ 1 for all t since |tz|<1.\"\n          :needed-because \"After inserting into the integral, the absolute value is controlled.\"}\n         {:name \"elementary integral\"\n          :meaning \"∫_0^1 t dt = 1/2.\"\n          :needed-because \"Finishes the estimate once |f'(tz)| ≤ 1 is in place.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Fundamental theorem for line integrals of analytic functions\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 expression f(z)=∫ z f'(tz) dt\"\n             :why-this-now \"Reduces the estimate to bounding an integral of f'.\"\n             :lean-target \"analytic_radial_integral\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib has `Complex.integral_cexp` etc; may need a short lemma for the radial path formula.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Bounding the integral with |f'| ≤ 1\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 inequality\"\n             :why-this-now \"Apply the triangle inequality and compute the elementary integral.\"\n             :lean-target \"schwarz_like_bound\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Only basic calculus/algebra; should be routine.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Analytic functions on the unit disk with f(0)=f'(0)=0 and |f'|≤1 satisfy |f(z)|≤|z|^2/2.\"\n             :formal-name \"disk_derivative_bound_implies_quadratic\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ f : ℂ → ℂ, (∀ z ∈ Metric.ball 0 1, AnalyticAt ℂ f z) ∧ f 0 = 0 ∧ deriv f 0 = 0 ∧ (∀ z ∈ Metric.ball 0 1, Complex.abs (deriv f z) ≤ 1) → ∀ z ∈ Metric.ball 0 1, Complex.abs (f z) ≤ Complex.abs z * Complex.abs z / 2\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Exactly formalizes the disk estimate stated in the exam problem.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"disk_derivative_bound_implies_quadratic\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ f : ℂ → ℂ, (∀ z ∈ Metric.ball 0 1, AnalyticAt ℂ f z) ∧ f 0 = 0 ∧ deriv f 0 = 0 ∧ (∀ z ∈ Metric.ball 0 1, Complex.abs (deriv f z) ≤ 1) → ∀ z ∈ Metric.ball 0 1, Complex.abs (f z) ≤ Complex.abs z * Complex.abs z / 2\"\n              :informal-clause \"Estimate |f(z)| ≤ |z|^2/2.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** The data look like Schwarz’ lemma, but the bound is on \\(f'\\), not \\(f\\). Students often try to shoehorn Schwarz by dividing by \\(z\\) or differentiating the Schwarz inequality, which doesn’t work without extra justification. The real challenge is finding a representation of \\(f\\) that explicitly uses \\(f'\\).\n\n**Key insight.** Integrate \\(f'\\) along the straight segment from \\(0\\) to \\(z\\):\n\\[\nf(z)=\\int_0^1 \\frac{d}{dt}f(tz)\\,dt=\\int_0^1 z f'(tz)\\,dt.\n\\]\nThen \\(|f(z)|\\le |z|\\int_0^1 |f'(tz)|\\,dt \\le |z|\\int_0^1 t\\,dt = |z|^2/2\\), because \\(|tz|<1\\) implies \\(|f'(tz)|\\le 1\\).\n\n**Complete proof.** For \\(|z|<1\\) set \\(\\gamma(t)=tz\\). Analyticity gives \\(f(z)-f(0)=\\int_0^1 f'(\\gamma(t))\\gamma'(t)\\,dt\\), i.e. \\(f(z)=\\int_0^1 z f'(tz)\\,dt\\). Applying the triangle inequality and the hypothesis \\(|f'(w)|\\le 1\\) for \\(|w|<1\\) yields\n\\[\n|f(z)| \\le \\int_0^1 |z|\\,|f'(tz)|\\,dt \\le |z|\\int_0^1 t\\,dt = \\frac{|z|^2}{2}.\n\\]\nThus \\(|f(z)| \\le |z|^2/2\\) on the unit disk.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Main target (`formal-alignment.edn`): `disk_derivative_bound_implies_quadratic`.  \n- Plan (`proof-plan.edn`): two steps—prove the radial integral lemma (`analytic_radial_integral`), then apply the derivative bound plus an elementary integral to get the inequality.  \n- Stage 3 status: still “in progress.” Remaining Lean work is to encode the radial integral identity via `intervalIntegral` machinery and then apply `norm_integral_le_integral_norm`. No `sorry`s have been introduced yet; implementation will go into `Main.lean`.  \n- Stage write-up (`execute.md`) now contains the full proof, lemma graph, and Lean plan; `changelog.edn` records workspace init, Stage 1/2 completion, and Stage 3 pending.\n\n**What connects.** This is a special case of higher-order Schwarz lemmas: if \\(f(0)=\\dots=f^{(k-1)}(0)=0\\) and \\(|f^{(k)}|\\le M\\), then \\(|f(z)|\\le M |z|^k/k!\\). The “integrate along a radial segment” trick also underlies mean-value inequalities for harmonic functions and the Schwarz–Pick lemma. Keep it handy whenever you have a uniform derivative bound and need direct control of the function.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A93J06/Apm_v2_a93J06_1775002790071", :frame/id "apm-v2-a93J06-1775002790071", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :wo